1. OOPS: 
- PROCEDURAL PROGRAMMING:- procedures/methods are written
    -> fixed flow
    -> tightly coupled (depends on other funcs output)
- OBJECT ORIENTED PROGRAMMING:- objects are created
    -> loosely coupled (less dependency on other factors)
    -> faster than procedural and clear structure
    -> reusability. 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[DOUBT]: Procedural Programming follows top-down approach but OOP follows bottom-up approach. HOW???
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- MAIN ASPECTS: Classes, objects, access modifiers, inheritence, constructor, encapsulation, abstraction, polymorphism.
    - Class -> More like a blueprint/template of an object. 
        -> Has member functions and data members
        -> No physical existence.
        -> Eg: Fruits - CLASS 
    - Object -> Instance of a class. 
        -> Physical existence hota hai. 
        -> has properties and behaviours.  
        -> Eg: Apple, Mango, Orange - OBJECTS 
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/oops/Student.java]
    - 4 MAJOR PILLARS -> Encapsulation, Inheritence, Polymorphism and Abstraction. 
    - Inheritence -> reusing the functionalities of an existing class in a new class.
        -> Existing class - parent class / base class 
        -> New class - child class / derived class
        -> Child class will inherit all data members and member functions of parent class. 
    - Polymorphism -> existing in many forms with same name.
        -> Achieved by using method overloading and method overidding. 
        -> Method overloading is performed in the same class. 
        -> Method Overidding requires inheritence prop (both parent and child class).
    - Abstraction -> hiding imp implementation details and functionalities. 
        -> Achieved by using abstract classes and interfaces. 
        -> eg. Car => performs abstraction 
    - Encapsulation -> binding all DMs and MFs as a single unit. 
        -> Imp feature here is:- DATA HIDING. <implements info hiding - fields/DMs>
        -> eg. Class where DMs are private and MFs are public where we access data via getter-setters. 
    - Constructors -> object created and its gets automatically called. 
        -> Matches the name of class 
        -> no return type 
        -> Tried making all different constructors based on access modifiers. 
        -> public - object can be created from anywheree 
        -> protected - object can be created only in same package & sub-classes 
        -> default - object can be created only in same package `
        -> private - same class 
    
- KEY POINTERS REQUIRED: 
    - CLASS -> FIELDS + METHODS
        -> Uses . operator to access attributes. 
            -> ObjectReference.variableName;
            -> ObjectReference.MethodName();
        -> FIELDS: 
            -> data members
            -> {access_modifier} {data-type} attribute_name;
            -> if static - no need of object (gets stored in METHOD AREA).
            -> if not static - need object to access it. [SAM<DOUBT>]
            -> if a field is marked as [FINAL], then trying to change it will give [COMPILATION-ERROR].
        -> METHODS: 
            -> member functions
            -> {access_modifier} {return-type} method_name(attributes list) {....}
            -> if static - definition is stored in METHOD AREA. 
                -> stores its local vars in stack memory just like normal method when invoked. 
                -> ACCESSING - {class-name}.{method-name}(params)
            -> if not static - need object to invoke it.
                -> ACCESSING - obj.method (params)
            -> All methods can access all the fields of the same class irrespective of its access modifier. 
    - Instance Variables -> non-static data members. stored in heap memory within object area. 
        -> Lifetime - till object is there in heap memory.
    - Class Variables -> Static data members. 
        -> Lifetime - till class definition is loaded in memory.
    - Local Variables -> eg. defined in a method.
        -> Lifetime - till method ends. 
    - Access Modifiers -> default, public , protected, private 
        -> Default - no accesss modifier is written. 
    - this -> reference to the object of the current cls. 
        -> Differentiates instance vars from local vars
        -> this.age = age 
        -> this(4) => is used to call any other constructor from a constructor of same class. => EXPLICIT CONSTRUCTOR INVOCATION.
    - finalize() -> its called for cleanup process and allows objects to terminate properly. 
        -> JVM may/maynot call it before object destruction. 
        -> Garbage Collection is automatically done by JVM. 
            -> Any unreachable allocated heap memory is eligible for GC.
        -> Depreciated now due to its unpredictability. 

- INFO TO GAIN: 
    - BASIC INFO: 
        -> package declaration should be at the top. 
        -> import statements should be next. 
        -> file can have only one public cls. 
        -> file can have multiple non public classes. 
        -> class declaration should only be after package declaration and then import statements. 
        -> By default, [FIELDS] in Interface are [public-static-final]    
            -> [WHY??] - Interfaces fields are used by classes (so needs to be public.), interfaces dont have objects (so static.), declared by interfaces cant be changed. its a contract (so final.)
        -> By default, [METHODS] in Interface are [public-abstract]
            -> [WHY??] - Interface Methods are implemented by classes (so needs to be public.), interface methods must be implemented (so abstract.)
        -> Classes and interface cannot be private or protected. 
        -> Classes can have protected methods and fields. but interfaces cannot. 
            -> [WHY??] - Methods of class can still be invoked using getters-setters. same with fields. 
            -> But Interface is a contract, it can implemented anywhere, within or out the package. so it needs to be public abstract(methods) and public static final (fields). 

    - PASS BY VALUE and PASS BY REFERENCE: 
        -> Java has only pass-by-value. not pass-by-reference. 
        -> If we pass an var as param, it will simply create another local var and store it in. 
        -> If we pass a reference as param, it will create another ref var and store that address in it. 
        -> So no pass by reference.
        -> Unlike C++ which used to point to same var which was passed as param using concept of REFERENCE VAR.
    - PASSING VAR LENGTH ARGUMENTS:- 
        -> only one such argument can be used. 
        -> should be the last one. 
        -> uses ellipsis (...)
        -> eg: double... numbers
        -> passed methodName(3,5,6.7,45,4.6) => internally a double array will be created in heap memory and ref gets stored in stack memory - in ref var numbers. 
        -> Suppose, if we have an array with no reference var in stack memory then that array is not reachable. ELIGIBLE FOR GARBAGE COLLECTION....
    - FINAL KEYWORD: 
        -> VARIABLE - we cannot change its value. 
        -> METHOD - we cannot override / change its implementation. 
        -> CLASS - no child (extend / implements)

- NESTED CLASS: 
    - Outer class can have access modifier -> public/default
        - [WHY-NO-PRIVATE?] -> if cls is private, its only visible in the same class itself. NO ONE CAN ACCESS. NO meaning. 
        - [WHY-NO-PROTECTED] -> protected means same package + sub-classes. but to extend this cls, u should first have the visibility of this cls wherever we are trying to extend. so if a sub-cls is made in different package, it wont be visible there initially, so JAVA restricts it. 
    - Inner class can have -> public/protected/default/private 
        - [WHY?] -> ATLEAST they will be accessible in its outer class. 
    - Access Modifiers of classes define its visibilty. 
        - If inner one is private -> MAX visibilty is OUTER CLASS. 
        - Public -> everywhere   
        - Default -> same package 
        - Protected -> Same package + sub classes. 
    - Static/Non-Static just decides whether object is required or not. 
    - Accesss Modifiers of constructor decides just the OBJECT CREATION. 
        - So, If constructor is private. we can still access that class ke obj ka method outside. 
        - But, if class is private, then nothing can be done. NO ACCESS...
        - If constructor is private: We have 3 methods: 
            - STATIC FIELD - ek hi object banega overall. 
                - ref stored in <Method area>. obj in <heap>.
                - make an object of the cls as a DM. declare it <public> and <static>.
                - [IMP] -> PUBLIC defined hai. anyone can change it. SO <Less secure>.
            - SINGLETON CLASS -> ek hi object banega iss cls ka. 
                - make an object of the cls as a DM. declare it <private> and <static>.
                - use getter method to return this object. 
            - FACTORY METHOD -> object is created inside that getter func. so as many we want it can be created.
