- AGGREGATION:- 
    - Relationship between two classes where one class contains an instance of another class. 
    - Follows HAS-A Relationship. 
    - WHY NEEDED ?? Code reusability. 
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/aggregation]

- POLYMORPHISM: 
    - Ability to take on multiple forms (show different behav) based on situations. Can be an object or a method. 
    - Eg: Animal p = new cat(); 
        p = new dog(); 
        - Reference variable same hi hai (Animal p) but usne jis object ka reference store kiya hai wo alag alag hai. 
        - Based on situation, isne bhi apna behav/form badal diya. 
    - Any JAVA objects with more than 1 IS-A relationship is considered to be <polymorphic>. 
    - All JAVA objects are polymorphic. 
        - cat IS A cat. 
        - cat IS A object. 
        - These two are fixed for every object. 

    - REFERENCE VARIABLE: 
        - Cannot change the type of reference variable once assigned. 
        - Can point to any object of its cls type or its subcls type. 
        - Can be of a class or an interface. 
        - Defines what we can access. 

    - TYPES OF POLYMORPHISM:
        - Compile time polymorphism / Static Polymorphism 
            - performed by [method-overloading]
        - Run time polymorphism / Dynamic Polymorphism 
            - performed by [method-overriding]

    - Virtual Method -> Wo methods jo runtime pe call hote hain based on object type are virtual methods.

    - OVERRIDING: 
        - means to override the functionality of an existing method. 
        - WHY NEEDED ?? to define a behav specific to child cls. 
        - WHILE OVERRIDING, we can have:
            - different access modifers - provided child cls AM has [equal-or-more] visibility. 
            - different return types - provided child cls return type follows [is-a] relationship with return type of parent. 
            - NO, we need to have <same> [list-of-paramters].
        - TWO PRIMARY CONDITIONS FOR OVERRIDDING: 
            - method is inherited to child cls. 
            - Redefined by child cls.
        - static methods are not overridden 
            - they belong to class not object. settled during the compile time itself. 
            - no requirement of object to call those methods. 
            - parent and child can have same name static methods. BASED ON REFERENCE TYPE - will be decided in COMPILE TIME BINDING itself, that which method will be called.
        - While overridding, both methods have to be [non-static]. Koi bhi ek static hogya -> ERROR.
        - If we mark a method as [final], then we cannot override it. 
            - But we can call the parent one still.
        - If we mark a method as [private], then we cannot override it. 
            - Also we cannot call the parent method -> NO VISIBILITY due to PRIVATE AM. 
        - CONSTRUCTOR cannot be overridden. 
            - [WHY??] -> because it is not inherited. 
        - Use @Override
            - Performs compile time error checks. 
            - Catches bugs early.
        [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/polymorphism]

    - METHOD OVERLOADING: 
        - two or more methods with same METHOD NAME but with different params, is METHOD OVERLOADING. 
        - OVERLOADING = same name + diff params list. 
        - Return type, Access Modifier, static/non-static doesn't matter. 
        [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/polymorphism]

    - DYNAMIC BINDING: 
        - Process in which linking between METHOD CALL and METHOD IMPLEMENTATION is solved at runtime is called as DYNAMIC BINDING. 
        - Late Binding 
        - Decided based on type of objects not reference type. 
        - ALL Virtual methods performs DYNAMIC BINDING. 
        - if super keyword is used inside child class non static method - it calls parent ones. 
        [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/polymorphism/overriding] 
    
    - STATIC BINDING: 
        - Process in which linking between METHOD CALL and METHOD IMPLEMENTATION is solved at compile time is called as STATIC BINDING. 
        - Early Binding 
        - Static/Final/Private methods - decided during compile time. 
        - Decided based on type of reference not object type. 
        - Method Overloading is STATIC BINDING. 
            - Compile time mai hi usne signature match kiya and link kardiya.
        [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/polymorphism/overloading] 
    
    - INSTANCE INITIALIZER BLOCK:
        - Block declared inside a class to declare data members
        - Executed once per object. 
        - Executed before constructor call. 
        - public class Tester {
            public int a;
            { 
                a = 10; 
            }   
            Tester(){
                a = 20;
            }
        }
            - Initialised as 10 due to IIB then got overridden by constructor (20). 

        - In case of child class, first parent constructor is called, then IIB, then child constructor.

- ABSTRACT CLASSES: 
    - [abstract] keyword is used to achieve this. 
    - WHAT IT CAN HAVE??
        - Abstract methods 
        - Concrete Methods (with implementation/body)
        - Constructors 
        - Static vars and methods.
        - Final methods (concrete ones) 
        - Instance vars. 
    - WHAT IT CANNOT HAVE?
        - Cannot be declared final 
            - [WHY??] because we need abstract classes to be extended to be of any use. final restricts it. 
        - Instance cannot be created. 
            - [WHY??] because it may/maynot have implementations of many methods. 
        - Cannot be declared private 
            - [WHY??] No visibility outside the same abstract class, so cant extend it. 
    - ABSTRACT METHOD: 
        - In any class, if there is even one abstract method, then it has to be declared as an abstract class. 
        - Class extending abstract class should provide implementation of all abstract methods. 
        - ABSTRACT METHOD -> abstract void show(); -> methods without body.
        - Any class inheriting the current class must either override the abstract method or declare itself as abstract.  [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/abstraction/special.java]
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/abstraction/abstract_class.java] 
        
- ABSTRACTION: 
    - Hiding the implementation details from users, only functionality will be provided. 
    - Users know what it does -- not how it does?
    - Achieved by using ABSTRACT CLASSES and INTERFACES. 
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/abstraction/abstract_class.java] 

- INTERFACES: 
    - WHAT IT CAN HAVE??
        - Abstract methods ✅ (by default all are abstract)
        - Concrete Methods ✅ (use default keyword.)
        - Constructors ❌
        - Static vars. ✅ (by default vars are static)
        - static methods. ✅ 
        - Final methods ❌
        - Instance vars. ❌
    - Method Body exists -> static methods and default methods. 
